Global data sources which include information pertinent to the Greater Serengeti-Mara Ecosystem 

# Moderate Resolution Imaging Spectroradiometer (MODIS) # 

https://modis.gsfc.nasa.gov/

Satellite data from NASA; particularly valuable include vegetational indices such as NVDI. Can also be downloaded from https://earthexplorer.usgs.gov/. For step-by-step instructions on how to download and use NDVI data, see https://lionstats.wordpress.com/2018/05/02/downloading-and-extracting-ndvi-values/ 


# Fire Information and Resource Management System (FIRMS) Fire Map # 

https://firms.modaps.eosdis.nasa.gov/

FIRMS Fire Map allows you to interactively browse the full archive of global active fire detections from MODIS and VIIRS. Near real-time fire data are available within approximately 3 hours of satellite overpass and imagery within 4-5 hours. 


# Open Street Map # 

https://www.openstreetmap.org

OpenStreetMap is a collaborative project (wiki) to create a free editable map of the world. Over two million volunteer users collect and contribute data using manual survey, GPS devices, aerial photography, and other free sources. Maps of the Serengeti region include locations of staff housing, roads, airstrips, and other man-made features. 


# Harvey Maps # 

https://www.harveymaps.co.uk/acatalog/Serengeti-YHAMSE.html#SID=33

Place to purchase the official management map and visitor guide of Serengeti, Masai Mara, Ngorogoro and Oldupai, made in collaboration with Frankfurt Zoological Society. Includes information on  migration patterns, wildlife, the peoples of the Serengeti, climate, landscape and habitat. 
